  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Abridged History of Goryeo
  author: Lee Geuk-gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servants humbly submit that the annalistic method has its foundation in the Spring and Autumn Annals of Zuo Qian, while the biographical-imperial method originated with Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian. Since Ban Gu's time, all historians have followed and revered the path of Sima Qian, never deviating from it—and for good reason, for his scope was vast and his work achieved completeness. Yet it cannot escape the fault of excessive length and laborious obscurity. Thus it is that historians possess both strengths and weaknesses, and none can be entirely abandoned.

    Goryeo arose in the waning days of the Tang, subduing rival powers through martial prowess and winning the hearts of the people through magnanimity. It established a great dynasty and bequeathed it to posterity. In time, it instituted sacrifices at the state altars, established governing codes, promoted schools, instituted civil examinations, and created the Chancellery to oversee all affairs—thus establishing proper governance. It dispatched inspectors to scrutinize the provinces and prefectures, restraining corruption. The military and civilian administrations were organized with wisdom, the system of land grants honored meritorious lineages, laws and punishments were perfected, and order prevailed both within and without. The people flourished and wealth increased. Such was the flowering of prosperity!

    Yet from the middle period onward, the state could no longer bear its burden. Within, it was corrupted by court favorites; without, it was controlled by scheming ministers. Powerful enemies invaded in succession, war ravaged the land, and finally imposters usurped the throne until the Wang royal house received no offerings. Though Gongyang attempted restoration, weakness and confusion led only to ruin. Truly, Heaven sends forth the true sovereign to bring peace to our people—a work beyond mere human effort.

    Taejo, the Great King of Kangheol, first commanded his ministers to compile the History of Goryeo. Taejong, the Great King of Gongjeong, later ordered the correction of errors, yet the work remained unfinished. Sejong, the Great King of Jangheon, with his godly wisdom and illuminating virtue, commanded us to gather able associates and establish the bureau of compilation, saying: "First complete the comprehensive history, then proceed to the annalistic form." We accepted this charge with reverence and diligence. Alas, before the work was perfected, he withdrew from us.

    The present sovereign, in filial succession to his predecessor's intention, commanded us to complete the task. Having received orders from the late king, we could not presume to decline through false modesty. In the autumn of the year Shinmui, the work at last was finished. We then gathered the records pertaining to moral education and the institutions worthy of emulation, pruned the excess, preserved the essential, arranged events by year and chronicle, and made it convenient for consultation. Thus four hundred and seventy-five years and twenty-two reigns are encompassed without omission, both the detailed and the concise are complete, and the form of historical writing is finally, in broad outline, established.

    Though our language is plain and our arrangement imperfect, yet in the encouragement of virtue and censure of vice, there is some small benefit to the art of governance. In your leisure hours, should you deign to examine this work, and cultivate the noble virtue of studying antiquity and broaden the great principles of statecraft, then will all your people receive the blessing of your wisdom—a fortune beyond measure.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Annals of Zuo Qian (Zuo zhuan) and Sima Qian's Records of the Grand Historian (Shiji) represent the two foundational historiographical traditions in East Asia—the annalistic and biographical-imperial methods respectively.
  - key: ''
    value: This preface was written to present the Abridged History of Goryeo (Goryeosa Jeolyo) to the Korean throne, likely during the early Joseon period when the compilation was completed.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'year Shinmui' refers to 1391 CE, when the work was completed during the reign of King Sejong.
